tem was discovered<ref name="Mann & Ebeling">{{cite journal |title=X-ray-optical classification of cluster mergers and the evolution of the cluster merger fraction |last=Mann |first=Andrew |author2=Harald Ebeling |date=March 2012 |bibcode=2012MNRAS.420.2120M|arxiv = 1111.2396 |doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2966.2011.20170.x }}</ref> during the [[Massive Cluster Survey]], MACS.<ref name="MACS">{{cite journal |title=MACS: A Quest for the Most Massive Galaxy Clusters in the Universe |last=Ebeling |first=Harald |author2=Alastair Edge |author3=J. Patrick Henry |date=June 2001 |bibcode=2001ApJ...553..668E|arxiv = astro-ph/0009101 |doi = 10.1086/320958 }}</ref> This cluster causes [[gravitational lensing]] of distant galaxies producing multiple images.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Free Form Lensing Implications for the Collision of Dark Matter and Gas in the Frontier Fields Cluster MACSJ0416.1-2403 |last=Diego |first=Jose M. |date=4 June 2014 |bibcode=2015MNRAS.447.3130D |doi=10.1093/mnras/stu2660 |arxiv=1406.1217 |volume=447 |journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society |pages=3130–3149}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://phys.org/news/2014-07-mass-distant-galaxy-cluster-precise.html |title=New mass map of a distant galaxy cluster is the most precise yet |date=24 July 2014 |accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref> In 2015, the galaxy cluster was announced as [[gravitational lens|gravitationally lensing]] the most distant [[galaxy]] (''z'' = 12).{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} Based on the distribution of the multiple image copies, scientists have been able to deduce and map the distribution of [[dark matter]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cho|first1=Adrian|title=Scientists unveil the most detailed map of dark matter to date|journal=Science|date=2017|doi=10.1126/science.aal0847|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/03/scientists-unveil-most-detailed-map-dark-matter-date}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Natarajan|first1=Priyamvada|last2=Chadayammuri|first2=Urmila|last3=Jauzac|f