{{Infobox Website | name = Slooh.com | logo = <!-- [[Image:logo.png|Website logo]] --> | screenshot = | caption = <!-- Screenshot of Slooh.com as of <date> --> | url = [http://www.slooh.com/ slooh.com] | alexa = {{DecreasePositive}} 46,102 ({{as of|2014|4|1|alt=April 2014}})<ref name="alexa">{{cite web|url= http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/slooh.com |title= Slooh.com Site Info | publisher= [[Alexa Internet]] |accessdate= 2014-04-01 }}</ref><!--Updated monthly by OKBot.--> | commercial = Yes | type = [[Service provider]] | language = | registration = Yes | owner = Michael Paolucci (Founder) | author = | launch date = June 26, 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/slooh.com|title=slooh.com - Traffic Details from Alexa|accessdate=October 9, 2009}}</ref> | current status = Active | revenue = | content license = }}
'''Slooh''' is a [[robotic telescope]] service that can be viewed live through a [[web browser]] with [[Adobe Flash|Flash]] [[browser plug-in|plug-in]]. It was not the first robotic telescope, but it was the first that offered "live" viewing through a telescope via the [[World Wide Web|web]].<ref>{{Cite web | last = New York NY (SPX) | first = | title = Discovery.com Promotes Slooh Online Telescope To Readers | date = 9 March 2005 | url=http://www.spacedaily.com/news/telescopes-05h.html | accessdate = 19 January 2017}}</ref> Other online telescopes traditionally email a picture to the recipient. The site has a patent on their live image processing method.<ref>{{ cite patent |country=US |number=7194146 |status=patent}}</ref> Slooh is an online astronomy platform with live-views and telescope rental for a fee.<ref name=rodenberg>[http://www.popularmechanics.com/science/space/telescopes/4349969 Cassie Rodenberg, "The Best in Armchair Astronomy", '''Popular Mechanics''' (March 22, 2010) - Accessed October 2010]</ref> Observations come from a global network of telescopes located in places including [[Spain]] and [[Chile]].<ref name=rodenberg/>
The name Slooh comes from the word "[[slew (spacecraft)|slew]]" to indicate the movement of a [[telescope]], modified with "ooh" to express pleasure and surprise.
==History== The service was founded in 2002 by Michael Paolucci. As of October 2009, Paolucci remains as chairman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slooh.com/about.php|title=SLOOH - About Us|accessdate=October 9, 2009}}</ref> The service went online December 25, 2003 but was not available to the public until 2004.
==Participating observatories== The original [[astronomy|astronomical]] [[observatory]] is located on the island [[Tenerife]] in the [[Canary Islands]] on the [[volcano]] called [[Teide]]. The site is at the {{convert|2300|m|adj=on}}<!--altitude is expressed in metres--> [[elevation]]<ref>{{cite web|title=SLOOH - System Specifications|url=http://www.slooh.com/specs.php|accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref> and situated away from city [[light pollution]]. This (Canary Islands) site includes 2 [[domes]], each with 2 telescopes. Each dome has a high-[[magnification]] telescope and a [[field of view|wide-field]] telescope. One dome is optimized for [[planet]]ary views (e.g., more magnification and a different [[Charge-coupled device|CCD]]), and the other is optimized for [[deep sky objects]] (e.g., less magnification, more light sensitive CCD). Each dome offers 2 [[telescope|telescopic]] views: one high magnification (narrow field) view through a {{convert|14|inch|adj=on}} [[Celestron]] [[Schmidt-Cassegrain telescope]]; and a wide view through either a [[telephoto lens]] or an [[Apochromat|APO]] [[refractor]]. In 2012, the Slooh.com Canary Islands Observatory was assigned [[List of observatory codes|observatory code]] G40.<ref>{{cite web|title=MPC 80331- 81072|url=https://www.minorplanetcenter.net/iau/ECS/MPCArchive/2012/MPC_20121029.pdf|publisher=The Minor Planet Center|accessdate=2017-12-22}}</ref>
On February 14, 2009, Slooh launched a second observatory in the hills above [[La Dehesa]], [[Chile]]. This site offers views from the [[Southern Hemisphere]]. In 2014, the Slooh.com Chile Observatory was assigned [[List of observatory codes|observatory code]] W88.<ref>{{cite web|title=MPC 89089- 89388|url=https://www.minorplanetcenter.net/iau/ECS/MPCArchive/2014/MPC_20140810.pdf|publisher=The Minor Planet Center|accessdate=2017-12-22}}</ref>
Unlike [[Google Sky]] which features images from the [[Hubble Space Telescope]], Slooh can take new images of the sky with its telescopes.<ref name=rodenberg/>
