{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}} {{Use British English|date=February 2014}} {{Infobox television | | show_name = Stephen Hawking: Master of the Universe | runtime =48 mins | creator = | composer = | starring = [[Stephen Hawking]] | narrated = | country = United Kingdom | network = [[Channel 4]] | first_aired = | last_aired = | num_episodes = 2 }}
'''''Stephen Hawking: Master of the Universe''''' is a documentary [[television series]] produced by the [[television]] broadcaster [[Channel 4|Channel 5]]. The subject of the series is British [[theoretical physics|theoretical physicist]] [[Stephen Hawking]], known for his work on [[black holes|black hoes]], who is also the presenter of the series. The series includes interviews with astrophysicist [[Kim Weaver]], [[Bernard Carr]], a student of Hawking's, and three theoretical physicists: [[Michio Kaku]], [[Edward Witten]], known for his work on [[superstring theory]], and [[Lisa Randall]]. The first episode premiered in 2008, twenty years after the publication of Hawking's bestselling [[popular science]] book ''[[A Brief History of Time]]''.<ref name="c4"/> The title is derived from a ''[[Newsweek]]'' cover,".<ref name="bio">{{cite book |title= Stephen Hawking: An Unfettered Mind |last= Ferguson |first= Kitty |year= 2012|publisher= Macmillan |location= |isbn= 9781137000224 | page= 146 }}</ref>
The series consisted of two episodes. The first describes Hawking's personal life, his challenges in overcoming his [[motor neurone disease]], and his career in physics. It covers his childhood, education, marriage, family life, and his work on the [[Big Bang]] and [[black holes]]. The second episode discusses [[string theory]] and [[supersymmetry]].<ref name="c4">{{cite web |url= http://www.channel4.com/programmes/master-of-the-universe |title= Stephen Hawking: Master of the Universe |publisher= Channel 4 |accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref> Both episodes are 48 minutes long, and premiered as half hour-long programes.<ref name="c4"/> The series was released on CD by Channel 4 in the UK as a [[DVD region code#Region codes and countries|Region 2]], one disc-DVD (B00140SGOM) on 18 March 2008.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hawking|first=Stephen|title=Prof Steven Hawking: A brief history of time|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/large-hadron-collider/3326879/Prof-Steven-Hawking-A-brief-history-of-time-contd.html|accessdate=31 July 2012|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=26 Feb 2008}}</ref>
==Reception== The premiere of the first episode attracted 1.9&nbsp;million viewers, and was considered a success.<ref>{{cite news |title= Five off to a strong start with Breaking into Tesco |first= David |last=Darren|url= http://www.brandrepublic.com/News/787811/Five-off-strong-start-Breaking-Tesco/|newspaper=Brand Republic|date= 4 March 2008|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref> The second episode had 1.7&nbsp;million viewers.<ref>{{cite news |title= The Fixer brings crime drama joy to ITV |first= Daniel|last=Farey-Jones|url= http://www.brandrepublic.com/news/789621/Fixer-brings-crime-drama-joy-ITV/|newspaper=Brand Republic|date= 11 March 2008|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref> James Walton of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' wrote a positive review of the first episode, saying that it "hadn’t done a bad job of trying to explain advanced physics to the science novice," even if it was "extremely difficult stuff."<ref>{{cite news |title= Last night on television: Stephen Hawking: Master of the Universe |first= James |last=Walton |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/3671613/Last-night-on-television-Stephen-Hawking-Master-of-the-Universe-Channel-4-The-Palace-ITV1.html|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date= 4 March 2008|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref> Philip Wakefield, a television critic for ''[[stuff.co.nz]]'', listed the first episode in his "Top TV picks", calling it "the neatest illustration of Einstein’s theory of relativity I’ve ever seen."<ref>{{cite news |title= Top 10 TV picks: December 2–8 |first= Philip |last=Wakefield |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/742244|newspaper=stuff.co.nz|date= 1 December 2008|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref> Sam Wollastan of ''[[The Guardian]]'' was more critical of the series, but did praise it for showing "the little glimpses of Prof Hawking's private life, like sharing a takeaway curry with a group of adoring young disciples."<ref>{{cite news |title= Last night's TV: Stephen Hawking: Master of the Universe |first= San |last=Wollastan |url= https://www.theguardian.com/culture/tvandradioblog/2008/mar/04/lastnightstvstephenhawking |newspaper=The Guardian|date= 3 March 2008|accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref>
